Did 2020 surpass the calamity of the 1918 flu pandemic?

Lets take a look


On April 23rd, the New York Times published an interesting analysis purporting to show that the global COVID-19 pandemic had upended a century of patterns of death and resulted in a calamity [of excess mortality] surpassing the 1918 Spanish flu pandemic.

This is a screenshot of the header & main figure supporting this claim.

As the Spanish flu pandemic is though to have killed 17-100 million people worldwide at a time when the worlds population was about one fourth its current size; and since the current global death toll of COVID-19 is around 3.1 million, this claim seemed a tiny bit far-fetched.

Lets unpack it.

The data

The first thing we can do is download data for the U.S. age-adjusted death rates through time.

The age-adjusted death rate is just the mortality rate for a given population, adjusted to match the age-distribution of another. Age-adjustment is a necessary standardization method required to compare mortality rates through time or between populations with different demographic distributions. This is because mortality increases with age, and thus a population with a higher median age (like Japan, for instance) will tend to have a higher crude death rate, even if the rate for any particular age is lower overall! In the U.S. the CDC National Center for Health Statistics compiles this data which are age-adjusted to match the United States demographic distribution of the 2000 census.

Through 2018, age-adjusted mortality rates for the U.S. can be downloaded directly from the NCHS.

To add the 2019 and 2020 death rates we can refer to this article in the CDC Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report by Ahmad et al. (2001).

Reiterating the Times analysis

My first challenge was to repeat the New York Times key analysis that was used to assert that 2020 was a more calamitous year of U.S. death than 1918.

Luckily, the reports author (Denise Lu) was kind enough to publish her specific methodology as follows:

So in other words, for each five years she fit a trendline (linear regression) to the U.S. age-adjusted death rate, then she predicted the death rate for the 6th year. Next she simply calculated the difference between the observed and predicted death rate as an excess in the rate for that year. Finally, she took the ratio of observed and predicted to compute the proportional excess (or percent above normal) in the age-adjusted mortality rate for each year. (1918 was not used to make predictions about other years, but no other special exceptions were made.)

That shouldnt be too hard to repeat. Lets try it! Heres my graph.

Figure 1. Re-iteration of New York Times analysis by Denise Lu.

Now go ahead compare my Figure 1 to the plot copied from the Times article, above, & you should see that they match precisely.

So far so good. Denise Lu and I are clearly using the same data. Thats a good start.

Problem 1: Proportional rather than absolute changes

My first qualm with the article is that for the Times analysis Lu elected to use proportional (i.e., percent), rather than absolute, changes in mortality rate.

This is an important decision & I would argue that it is inconsistent with how we normally evaluate risk. For instance, in the event of a plane crash you are nearly 100% more likely to die if seated in an aisle seat in the front or middle of the aircraft compared to a middle seat near the back. Nonetheless, because the risk of dying overall is so low, seasoned air travellers not only dont try to avoid sitting in the least safe seats of the aircraft (i.e., near the front) they often pay good money for the privilege!

By measuring proportional changes in the death rate, and by treating them as equivalent, Lu has decided that a 10% increase in the risk of death is a 10% increase in the risk of death, regardless of whether that change increased your annualized probability of dying from 0.7% to 0.77% (a change of 0.07%) or from 2% to 2.2% (a change that is nearly three times larger in absolute terms).

Lets re-do the Times analysis, but this time map absolute rather than proportional excesses in the death rate compared to predicted.

Everything is the same as before in this analysis; however, I no longer standardize by the predicted death rate, so excesses (or deficits) are expressed in deaths / 100,000 population, rather than as a percentage.

Figure 2. Changes in the U.S. age-adjusted death rate through time: re-iterating the methodology of the New York Times, but showing absolute, rather than proportional, change.

In this analysis we still see a very large effect of the 2020 pandemic, but in terms of a real change in deaths / 100,000 population, this effect is only about one-half the size of the excess associated with the 1918 Spanish flu pandemic.

Problem 2: Ignoring the change in mean

My second qualm with the Times piece is more philosophical than methodological, and it is that the article underplays the massive improvement in the death rate that weve seen over the past century.

In the figure below, Ive simply graphed the age-adjusted death rate / 100,000 population from 1900 to the present day.

Figure 3. United States age-adjusted death rate / 100,000 population through time from 1900-2020.

The reality that we see here is that the 2020 uptick in mortality indeed temporarily erased huge progress in reducing the death rate but it nonetheless only increased the rate back to about its 2003/2004 level. This can be seen by simply drawing a horizontal line from the 2020 death rate backwards in time.

We can likewise overlay our estimated mortality rate displacements (changes from normal), taken here from Figure 2, onto the generally decreasing death rate through time.

Once again, we see that the death rate ticked up in 2020 by a large amount but that the overwhelming trend over the past 120 years has nonetheless been towards a decreased death rate through time.

Figure 4. United States age-adjusted death rate / 100,000 population through time. The observed death rate is indicated by grey (normal) and red (excess) bars. Fewer deaths than expected are indicated by white bars.

Problem 3: Arbitrary definition of normal

In the context of Problem 2, above, I also take some exception to the somewhat arbitrary definition of normal.

According to Lus method, the expected death rate for a given year is obtained by fitting a trendline through the preceding five years (more on that below) and then using that trend line to predict mortality in the current year. Every preceding year is ignored.

This isnt the only imaginable way to compute the normal death rate. For instance, I joked on Twitter that normal (for me) could equally-well be defined as the average death rate over all years of my life from 1980 (when I was born) to the year preceding the pandemic, 2019.

But this definition of normal is a bit peculiar. I'm not too old almost a millenial so my normal could be the average death rate from 1980-2019: my years of life prior to the 2020 #Covid_19 pandemic. When I repeat the analysis using this normal, here's what I get. 4/5 pic.twitter.com/a2VBPqQfyx

Liam Revell (@phytools_liam) April 24, 2021

I wasnt serious, of course. But lets define normal a bit more narrowly say, as the 21st century death rate. In other words, the mean death rate for the years 2000 to 2019.

Figure 5. United States death rate above (or below) 2000-2019 average.

If we do that, we find that 2020 does have an excess of deaths compared to other recent years, but it is only very slightly above the 21st century average.

Of course, I understand that no demographer or epidemiologist would define normal mortality in this way. But Im equally confident, however, that the majority of the Times readership is not aware of how dramatically the death rate has fallen overall, including in their lifetimes, and probably wouldnt guess that the age-adjusted death rate in 2020 was very similar in magnitude to the death rate in the year I graduated from college.

Problem 4: The regression approach

My final issue with the Times analysis by Lu is perhaps the most technical, and this is the regression approach that the author used to generate predicted death rate for each year.

Just as a reminder, Lu fit a linear regression model (a trendline, for the non-statisticians) to the observed death rates for the preceding 5 years to predict the death rate for the current year.

This is what those trendlines look like when I overlay them onto my graph from Figure 4, above.

Figure 6. United States age-adjusted death rate / 100,000 population through time. The observed death rate is indicated by grey (normal) and red (excess) bars. Fewer deaths than expected are indicated by white bars. The trendlines used to generate predicted death rates for each year are shown as blue lines on the graph.

Here, the trouble arises when we zoom in on the five year periods before the 1918 Spanish flu pandemic and the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic.

Figure 7. Same as Figure 6, but zoomed in to the decades of 1910-1920 and 2010-2020.

What we see first is that the trendline from 2015-2019 is decreasing, as it tends to do.

However, when we look at the five year period preceding the 1918 Spanish flu pandemic (and bucking the tendency of 120 years of data), the death rate was actually already increasing. (Im not sure what was going on from 1914-1918 that could account for this pattern!)

I decided to recreate Figure 4, showing excesses in the death rate through time. Here, however, Ill redefine normal to mean the average of the 10 year window (five years in each direction) on either side of the current year. (As I approached the limits of our data, 1900 & 2020, I simply shrunk the window on one side or the other.) I also excluded 1918 from the calculation of the expected number of deaths in any other year, following Lu, and I excluded 2020 from the calculation of normal as we approached the present.

Lets see how our results change:

Figure 8. Annual changes in the age-adjusted death rate / 100,000 population using a moving average.

Here we see that the effect on the death rate was about 4 as large in 1918 compared to in 2020!

After all the math, this actually makes logical sense since the U.S. population in 1918 was about 103 million people (around 30% its current value), and nearly 700,000 people are thought to have died of Spanish flu in the United States (not to mention, we had a war going on!).

So overall, was the death rate in 2020 the highest above normal since the early 1900s - even surpassing the calamity of the 1918 flu pandemic?

I would answer with a qualified no. Yes, the death rate of 2020 was indeed way above the current normal, but the overall death rate in 2020 was only about 1/3 of its 1918 value, and the amount of death above normal did not exceed the amount that occurred during the 1918 influenza pandemic in the U.S.
